The point I wish to worry is not whether our spirit is
covered as a war, but what America does, though all the fiction written and all the fiction years being trained in colleges, seem to remain opaque or vaporous.
How many of our classics, notoriously, deal not with American society, but its asocial margins?
A whale hunt on the high seas, a refugee boy, a black slave on a river raft, the outcast, tested crimp,
the expatriate heroes of Hemingway and Henry James, seeking fulfillment and aesthetic satisfaction everywhere but at home in the United States.
One can make too much of this, but assume it is somewhat true.
What might the reasons be?
Let me propose four.
One, with exceptions like Watkins and Irving and Wood and Dean Howells, who tend to bore austerity.
The American writer has few traditional ties to the power establishment of the country, and ordinarily distrusts and scorns its politicians, businessmen, bureaucrats, managers, and even its workers.
All those, in short, who make the society go are dismissed by a puritan idealism that seeks to compromise with end maneuvers of striving actuality as unworthy of sympathetic consideration.

Two, the ideal of a classical society, in which there is no aristocracy, no peasantry, no certain class, in a perverse way makes us less accessible to one another by depriving our imaginations of those colorful badges and mannerisms and assigned duties with which characterization can begin.
Three, the very triumph.
of American popular culture in this century coats the individual whom the writer would hold up to cultural study in an impervious skin of cultural cliché.

The crises of will and desire that occupy 19th century novels are, as it were, kidded away by the image-faturated modern consciousness, which has pre-experienced everything in the trivializing and building abundance of unearned sophistication
This weariness of knowingness was wonderfully captured in the fiction of the late Donald Barberman.
And for, perhaps a culture that never had a classic or meaningful epoch doesn't need one much to say about being human.
When, in a nation soundly founded on 18th century rationalism and 19th century laws of material exchange, almost Haitians have been stripped of superstitious loyalties and quixotic delusions
What is left is a bald consumer, an animal of purely selfish appetites and purely biological motives whose genetically determined life events scarcely warrant the glamorization of fiction.
For whatever reason, America remains something of a riddle to the practitioners of fiction, a tougher nut to crack than you would think.
Several able journalists
advise us simply to seize the beast by the horns, do some research, and conduct a few interviews, and lay out the facts in lively Zola-esque fashion.
And of course, facts should be collected.

Because it just goes to absolutely the heart of what's going on in our country.
